Marketing Analytics Process

Predictive Modeling Workflow

Random Forests

Why have one decision tree when you can have a forest of decision trees?

  • A decision trees branches result from rules on the predictor variables.
  • In each dataset, there can be predictor variables that dominate.
  • To avoid this, use a random subset of predictors for a given decision tree.
  • Do this a lot and combine the predictions of all the decision trees.

This is a random forest. In general, the idea of combining the predictions of many models is known as an ensemble.

Feature Engineering

  • Load the tidyverse and tidymodels packages.
  • Set the randomization seed.
  • Import the roomba_survey data.
  • Create segment again with three categories.
  • Select segment along with the related behaviors, shopping attitudes, gender, home type, neighborhood, marital status, and education predictors.
  • Split the data with prop = 0.75 and strata = segment.

# Import data, wrangle S1 into segment, and select predictors.
roomba_survey <- read_csv(here::here("Data", "roomba_survey.csv")) |> 
  rename(segment = S1) |> 
  mutate(
    segment = case_when(
      segment == 1 ~ "own",
      segment == 3 ~ "shopping",
      segment == 4 ~ "considering"
    ),
    segment = factor(segment)
  ) |> 
  select(
    segment, contains("RelatedBehaviors"), contains("ShoppingAttitudes"), 
    D1Gender, D2HomeType, D3Neighborhood, D4MaritalStatus, D6Education
  )

# Split data based on segment.
roomba_split <- initial_split(roomba_survey, prop = 0.75, strata = segment)

training(roomba_split)

We can use . for the predictors since weve selected everything we want in the previous step.

# Feature engineering.
roomba_recipe <- training(roomba_split) |>
  recipe(
    segment ~ .
  ) |>
  step_dummy(all_nominal(), -all_outcomes())

roomba_recipe

##  Recipe 
##

Fit the Model

Install the {randomForest} package in order to use rand_forest().

# Set the model, engine, and mode.
rf_model_01 <- rand_forest() |> 
  set_engine(engine = "randomForest") |> 
  set_mode("classification")

rf_model_01
## Random Forest Model Specification (classification)
## 
## Computational engine: randomForest

Create a workflow that combines the recipe and model and fit it.

# Create a workflow.
rf_wf_01 <- workflow() |> 
  add_recipe(roomba_recipe) |> 
  add_model(rf_model_01)

# Fit the workflow.
rf_fit_01 <- fit(rf_wf_01, data = training(roomba_split))

Evaluate Predictive Fit

For classification, again accuracy on the testing data is a natural measure of predictive fit.

# Compute model accuracy.
rf_fit_01 |> 
  predict(new_data = testing(roomba_split)) |>
  bind_cols(testing(roomba_split)) |>
  accuracy(truth = segment, estimate = .pred_class)
## # A tibble: 1  3
##   .metric  .estimator .estimate
##   <chr>    <chr>          <dbl>
## 1 accuracy multiclass     0.714

Cross-Validation

But what if were randomly including something weird in the training data that biases the model?

Similar to the idea of using a subset of predictors for each model in a random forest, lets repeatedly resample a subset of the training data, fit the model, and average predictions to get a better read on predictive fit.

This is called cross-validation. How many “folds” we have is how many times we split the training data.

Use v-fold cross-validation on the training data. Note the structure of the output. Each fold has its own training and validation data split.

# Use v-fold cross-validation based on segment.
roomba_cv <- vfold_cv(training(roomba_split), v = 10, strata = segment)

roomba_cv
## #  10-fold cross-validation using stratification 
## # A tibble: 10  2
##    splits           id    
##    <list>           <chr> 
##  1 <split [222/26]> Fold01
##  2 <split [223/25]> Fold02
##  3 <split [223/25]> Fold03
##  4 <split [223/25]> Fold04
##  5 <split [223/25]> Fold05
##  6 <split [223/25]> Fold06
##  7 <split [223/25]> Fold07
##  8 <split [224/24]> Fold08
##  9 <split [224/24]> Fold09
## 10 <split [224/24]> Fold10

Instead of fit(), we need a function made to deal with all of these resamples. Note this is actually a for loop. It might take a minute.

# Fit the resampled training data.
cv_fit_01 <- fit_resamples(rf_wf_01, resamples = roomba_cv)

Compute predictive fit across folds with a single function collect_metrics().

# Compute model accuracy.
cv_fit_01 |>
  collect_metrics()
## # A tibble: 2  6
##   .metric  .estimator  mean     n std_err .config             
##   <chr>    <chr>      <dbl> <int>   <dbl> <chr>               
## 1 accuracy multiclass 0.685    10  0.0116 Preprocessor1_Model1
## 2 roc_auc  hand_till  0.604    10  0.0249 Preprocessor1_Model1

Hyperparameter Tuning

Cross-validation is especially important when trying to tune hyperparameters. If we use the testing data to tune hyperparameters, were back to overfitting. Instead, lets use the validation data in each fold.

  • mtry number of predictors randomly sampled for each tree (default is the square root of the number of predictors)
  • trees number of trees in the ensemble (default is 500)
  • min_n minimum number of data points in a node to be split (default is 1)

# Set the model, engine, and mode.
rf_model_02 <- rand_forest(mtry = tune(), trees = tune(), min_n = tune()) |> 
  set_engine(engine = "randomForest") |> 
  set_mode("classification")

rf_model_02
## Random Forest Model Specification (classification)
## 
## Main Arguments:
##   mtry = tune()
##   trees = tune()
##   min_n = tune()
## 
## Computational engine: randomForest

Instead of fit_resamples(), we need a function made to deal with the grid of all possible tuning parameters. Note this is a for loop within a for loop. It might take a while.

# Update the workflow.
rf_wf_02 <- rf_wf_01 |> 
  update_model(rf_model_02)

# Tune the hyperparameters by using the cross-validation.
cv_fit_02 <- rf_wf_02 |> 
  tune_grid(resamples = roomba_cv)

The number of models weve just fit has exploded.

# Look at the number of models!
cv_fit_02 |> 
  collect_metrics(summarize = FALSE)

We need to select the best one. Fortunately, theres a function for that.

# Select the best fitting model.
cv_fit_best <- cv_fit_02 |> 
  select_best(metric = "accuracy")

cv_fit_best
## # A tibble: 1  4
##    mtry trees min_n .config              
##   <int> <int> <int> <chr>                
## 1     3   684    21 Preprocessor1_Model02

Now we can finalize our workflow.

# Finalize the workflow.
rf_wf_final <- rf_wf_02 |> 
  finalize_workflow(cv_fit_best)
  
rf_wf_final
##  Workflow 
## Preprocessor: Recipe
## Model: rand_forest()
## 
##  Preprocessor 
## 1 Recipe Step
## 
##  step_dummy()
## 
##  Model 
## Random Forest Model Specification (classification)
## 
## Main Arguments:
##   mtry = 3
##   trees = 684
##   min_n = 21
## 
## Computational engine: randomForest

Now we can fit the final workflow on the entire training data and look at the predictive fit using the testing data without overfitting.

# Fit the tuned workflow to the whole dataset.
rf_fit_02 <- fit(rf_wf_final, data = training(roomba_split))

# Compute model accuracy.
rf_fit_02 |> 
  predict(new_data = testing(roomba_split)) |>
  bind_cols(testing(roomba_split)) |>
  accuracy(truth = segment, estimate = .pred_class)
## # A tibble: 1  3
##   .metric  .estimator .estimate
##   <chr>    <chr>          <dbl>
## 1 accuracy multiclass     0.679
